Introduction¶

Fake news is a broad term and in this project and specifically in this notebook, we will dive into fake and real covid-19 tweets. We will see what data we have, how it was collected then we will have a basic understanding of the data. Next, we will explore the data by asking questions and coming up with hypotheses about the data. In addition to that, we shall analze a sample of data to see what potentional problems in the data. Last, we will display our findings in a short way to conclude the notebook.

Problem understanding¶

News can be in many different forms. For example, Newspapers, Magazines, TV and radio, Internet, News agencies and Alternative media. Now, there are some businesses that try to promote their products or to advertise a product and some publish fake, attractive or charming news as 'clickbait' and we tend to be curious when it comes to unusual things and so we read / check the content. For instance, in 1835 newspaper company claimed that they have found out creates live in moon (humans with wings) here is link for full article. That as a consequence allowed the company to be more popular which allowed them to promote and advertise more. Now this is one of the reasons why would certain group of people / a person publish fake news or misleading information. However, the influnce on the reader is usually harmful. For example, it could be that fake news regards healthy food suggest or recommend some types of food for people who suffer from kind of illness and if reader followed the suggestions that could be in fact harmful for them since news were fake in the first place. There are more scenarios obviously but this is where the problem lies. Fake news in general are published for the sake of obtaining profit most of the time and readers might believe misleading information which could influence their decisions.

In this research though, the focus will be on the news of covid-19 topic (tweets) and various topics of fake, legit articles published on the internet.

Research question¶

  • Based on the classified covid-19 tweets as fake and real with the tweet text being available 'How is it possible to predict whether a new tweet tend to be fake or real?'

With this question in mind, the part of predicting the reliability of covid-19 tweet should be clear (half of the project) and the other half (fake and legit internet articles) will be in another notebook.

Data requirement¶

In this section I will describe the obtained data, its format, the number of columns and rows in addition to a description of each column.

Description of obtained data¶

The dataset is about some tweets which was taken from Twitter (social media platform) and classified by the dataset owner(s) as fake and real tweets in 2021.

Format of the data¶

The acquired dataset of covid-19 tweets is in CSV-format which can be easily stored locally on the machine.

General information about the dataset¶

The acquired dataset of covid-19 tweets consists of 6420 rows and 3 columns.

The columns being as the following:

  • id, which represents a unique number for each tweet in the dataset.

  • tweet, which represents the text or body of what has been tweeted or sent via the Twitter platform.

  • label, which represents whether a tweet was considered to be fake or legit according to the dataset owner(s).

Data collection¶

In this section I will describe where, how the data was acquired and pontential problems could arise while attempting to acquire them in addition to some remarks.

Where the data can be obtained?¶

The data can be obtained through this link, which is a github repository where the dataset owner has uploaded as an open-source data in addition to their own version of classifying fake and real covid-19 tweets.

The dataset file name: Constraint_Train.csv

How the data can be obtained?¶

In the previous sub-section I provided a link to where the data can be obtained. However, after clicking the link you will need to either download the entire repository as ZIP file or use git to get the repository in your local machine. Please follow one of the two possible twos:

  1. recommend way (ZIP file)

  1. Cloning the repository:
  • This way you will be able to clone a copy of the entire repository via git command line. (first you will have to dowbload git).
  • Open a folder you desire to have the cloned repository in.
  • Copy the repository link.
  • Open the git commander and type 'git clone (repository link)' and hit enter.

Potential problems can be encountered?¶

The second approach of obtaining the repository can be a bit difficult to people who never worked with git before, therefore they can receive errors in command line due to some type errors or incorrect git setup. However, my research requires a labeled dataset as it will be the target variable in the project with that being said I shall attempt my best to reduce bias in this research as much as possible. Matplotlib, Matplotlib is a comprehensive library for creating static, animated, and interactive visualizations in Python. Matplotlib makes easy things easy and hard things possible.

Numpy It is a Python library that provides a multidimensional array object, various derived objects (such as masked arrays and matrices), and an assortment of routines for fast operations on arrays, including mathematical, logical, shape manipulation, sorting, selecting, I/O, discrete Fourier transforms, basic linear algebra, basic statistical operations, random simulation and much more.

Pandas pandas is a fast, powerful, flexible and easy to use open source data analysis and manipulation tool, built on top of the Python programming language.

re A regular expression (or RE) specifies a set of strings that matches it; the functions in this module let you check if a particular string matches a given regular expression

nltk NLTK is a leading platform for building Python programs to work with human language data. It provides easy-to-use interfaces to over 50 corpora and lexical resources such as WordNet, along with a suite of text processing libraries for classification, tokenization, stemming, tagging, parsing, and semantic reasoning, wrappers for industrial-strength NLP libraries, and an active discussion forum.

spacy spaCy is a free open-source library for Natural Language Processing in Python. It features NER, POS tagging, dependency parsing, word vectors and more.

langdetect A python library that allows you to identify the language in a given string.

wordcloud Word Cloud is a data visualization technique used for representing text data in which the size of each word indicates its frequency or importance.

CountVectorizer CountVectorizer is a great tool provided by the scikit-learn library in Python. It is used to transform a given text into a vector on the basis of the frequency (count) of each word that occurs in the entire text.

Findings¶

After counting the number of characters, words and sentences for each tweet I tried to find out what was the relationship between the length and the reliability. I found out that in the dataset there are outliers in terms of length and if you zoom in to where outliers are not in your scope range you would notice that the less characters in a tweet the higher probably of it being fake. The same logic applies for number of words and number of sentences. I also found out that the majority of tweets consists of only 1 sentence, an on average of 20 sentences. Whereas a tweet contains about 100 characters tends to be fake and 200 chacaters tends to be real.

hypothesis: I think that if the tweet has less length, it tends to be real because that means that the tweet more less like a summary which tend to true.

Therefore, the hypothesis was wrong the data shows that the less length the tweet is the higher chance of it being fake tweet.

That will allow me to generate a cloud visualization to see important words mentioned in both fake tweets and real tweets.

Visualize the corpse¶

In this sub-section I will use the grouped tweets text for each label (each corpus) and transform it into a matrix where each word indicate how important it is to the corpus and finally use WordCloud as data visualization to see important words for each label.

The following function takes in the data and title to spit out word cloud data visualization

In [145]:
# Function for generating word clouds
def generate_wordcloud(data,title):
  wc = WordCloud(width=400, height=330, max_words=150,colormap="Dark2").generate_from_frequencies(data)
  plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
  plt.imshow(wc, interpolation='bilinear')
  plt.axis("off")
  plt.title('\n'.join(wrap(title,60)),fontsize=13)
  plt.show()

I will create now a matrix where each row represent a word that was present in the corpus of each fake and real with the corresponding reliability. Also stop words such as 'The, I, you' are words that occur too often but does not actually influence what we are trying to do therefore I will remove them in the CountVectorizer parameter.

Hypothesis was: I think 'claim' is one of the top words mentioned in the fake tweets, whereas 'reported' in the top words mentioned in the real tweers as 'claim' usually indicate what is about to mentioned is not 100% correct and 'reported' often used to display finding after some kind of research.

  • Therefore the hypothesis was correct claim did appear on the important words of fake tweets corpus and reported did appear on the important words of real tweets corpus.

Things to be noticed¶

  • Text can be all lowered case.
  • Text contain punctuations example, review 1 contain dot at the end.
  • Some reviews contain hyperlinks. For example, review 20 mentioned this link https://t.co/cFx0MYEcFx .
  • Some text contain short contractions. For example, review 16: Note: It's and the expanded version of it is 'It is'.
  • Tweets contain hashtags. For example, review 7: this hash tag was mentioned @drharshvardhan and #CoronaUpdatesInIndia
  • Some tweets contain emojis. For example, review 13: contains this emjoi 📍
  • Some text contain digits. For example, review 18 mentioned that 50000 individuals

Note: Keep in mind that the model that is going to be created should give results according to keywords of the tweets, thus digits should not matter as covid-19 figures changes and there is no way for the model I am developing to distinguish the 'fake' or 'real' tweets based on the digits.

Findings¶

After analyzing a sample of the data we have derived that the text contain some problems such as capalization, punctuations, hyperlinks involved, short contractions (example, It's), different hash tags that start with @ or #, various emojis in the text and the text contain digits which would not be useful for us in the prediction section.

Therefore the list of fixes for the text as follows:

  1. Lowercase all the text
  2. Expand Contractions
  3. Remove hyperlinks
  4. Remove hashtags
  5. Remove punctuations
  6. Remove emojis
  7. Remove digits

After that we should have clean text, but in order to continue processing it we would need to remove stopwords as they appear often in text corpus while not indicating actual meaning and need to use lemmatization technique in order to bring the words from various tense forms into their base form (example. 'Went' --use lemma--> 'Go')

Conclusions¶

To conclude this notebook, although fake news is a broad term our focus in this research was on covid-19 tweets and online articles (which will be covered in different notebook.), fake news in general are published for the sake of obtaining profit most of the time and readers might believe misleading information which could influence their decisions.

The data we worked on contains 3 columns id,tweet,label and around 6420 rows while id indicate a unique identifier, tweet indicate text that was sent and the label indicate the reliability of the tweet. The label column was created by the dataset owner which is subjective and could be biased but this research require a labeled data. The dataset can be easily stored in machine locally due to its size and its format. There are no duplicate tweets and there is only 2 unique labels. The fake tweets is almost less a bit than half of the dataset and the real tweets is about 52% of the dataset which indicate balance in the target variable.

The majority of tweets consists of only 1 sentence, an on average of 20 sentences. Whereas a tweet contains about 100 characters tends to be fake and 200 chacaters tends to be real. The data does contain tweets which are not in english language. Words such as reported, confirmed, update and deaths appear often in real covid-19 tweets. While, words such as lockdown, vaccine, claim and cure appear often in fake covid-19 tweets.

The dataset contain text issues which can be fixed with the following methods:

  1. Lowercase all the text
  2. Expand Contractions
  3. Remove hyperlinks
  4. Remove hashtags
  5. Remove punctuations
  6. Remove emojis
  7. Remove digits
